The '''Portugal national football team''' ({{langx|pt|Seleção Portuguesa de Futebol}}) <!-- Please add the Portuguese pronunciation. It must be standard European Portuguese, the Portuguese from Portugal. --> has represented [[Portugal]] in men's international [[Association football|football]] competition since 1921. The national team is controlled by the [[Portuguese Football Federation]] (FPF), the governing body for [[football in Portugal]]. Portugal's home stadium is the [[Estádio Nacional]] in [[Oeiras, Portugal|Oeiras]], located next to its primary [[Training ground (association football)|training ground]] and the FPF headquarters (''[[Cidade do Futebol]]''), but the team usually plays its home matches in more [[List of football stadiums in Portugal|modern stadiums]] throughout the country, such as the [[Estádio da Luz]], [[Estádio José Alvalade]] and the [[Estádio do Dragão]]. The head coach is [[Roberto Martínez]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Demony |first=Catarina |date=15 December 2022|title=Portugal coach Santos leaves job after World Cup exit |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/sports/portugal-coach-fernando-santos-set-leave-job-after-world-cup-defeat-source-2022-12-15/ |access-date=15 December 2022 |archive-date=15 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221215192057/https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/sports/portugal-coach-fernando-santos-set-leave-job-after-world-cup-defeat-source-2022-12-15/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and the captain is [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], who holds the team records for most caps and most goals.

Portugal's first participation in a major tournament finals was at the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]], which saw a team featuring [[Ballon d'Or]] winner [[Eusébio]] finish in third place. Since 2000s, Portugal started an uninterrupted streak of qualification for every European Championship and World Cup finals, including a runners-up finish at [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]] on home soil. They experienced much of their success in the late 2010s to mid 2020s, during the captaincy of Ballon d'Or winner Cristiano Ronaldo, where they won their first-ever major trophy [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]] and the [[UEFA Nations League]] in [[2019 UEFA Nations League|2019]], hosting the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals|first finals]], and a record second time in [[2025 UEFA Nations League final|2025]].

Portugal is colloquially referred to as the ''Seleção das [[Coat of arms of Portugal|Quinas]]'' (a synecdoche based on the flag of the country) and has several notable rivalries with other national teams. These include [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], due to their shared history and close cultural ties;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/news/7851928/Portugal-0-Brazil-0-match-report.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/news/7851928/Portugal-0-Brazil-0-match-report.html |archive-date=11 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Portugal 0 Brazil 0: match report|first=Jeremy|last=Wilson|date=25 June 2010|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}{{cbignore}}</ref> [[Spain national football team|Spain]], due to their historical rivalry as Iberian neighbours;<ref name="Fanatics">{{Cite book|first=João Nuno |last=Coelho|title= Fanatics! Power, Identity and Fandom in Football|place=Londres|publisher=Routledge|year=1998|pages=158–172|chapter=“’On the Border’: Some Notes on Football and National Identity in Portugal|isbn=978-1-134-67729-0|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0-WFAgAAQBAJ&q=On+the+Border%27%3A+Some+Notes+on+Football+and+National+Identity+in+Portugal%22&pg=PA170|access-date=26 May 2014}}</ref> and [[France national football team|France]], due to several high-stake meetings between both teams at the Euro and World Cup.<ref name="rivalidade">{{cite web |date=5 July 2024 |title=From Xavier to Batta: how controversy shaped Portugal v France rivalry |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/article/2024/jul/05/how-controversy-shaped-portugal-v-france-rivalry-euro-2024 |access-date=30 September 2024 |work=[[The Guardian]] |language=en}}</ref>

==History==
{{Main|History of the Portugal national football team}}

===Early World Cup attempts===
Portugal were not invited to the [[1930 FIFA World Cup|1930 World Cup]], which only featured a finals stage and no [[FIFA World Cup qualification|qualification round]]. The team took part in the [[1934 FIFA World Cup qualification]], but failed to eliminate their Spanish opponents, aggregating two defeats in the two-legged round, with a 9–0 loss in [[Madrid]] and 2–1 loss in [[Lisbon]] for an aggregate score of 11–1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=5792|title=Spain vs Portugal, 11 March 1934, World Cup qualification|website=eu-football.info|access-date=23 September 2019|archive-date=13 June 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200613115646/https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=5792|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=5790|title=Portugal vs Spain, 18 March 1934, World Cup qualification|website=eu-football.info|access-date=23 September 2019|archive-date=13 June 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200613115645/https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=5790|url-status=live}}</ref>

In the [[1938 FIFA World Cup qualification]], the ''Seleção'' played one game against Switzerland held in neutral ground in [[Milan]]. They lost 2–1 and failed to qualify for the finals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scoreshelf.com/gjdb/en/Switzerland/World_Cup/1938fwcSUI_v_POR|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716020411/http://scoreshelf.com/gjdb/en/Switzerland/World_Cup/1938fwcSUI_v_POR|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 July 2011|title=Switzerland v Portugal : World Cup 1938 Qualifying Round|date=16 July 2011}}</ref> The [[World War II|Second World War]] delayed the World Cup until [[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950]] and subsequently, the national team rarely played.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/mens/worldcup/1950brazil |title=Brazil 1950 FIFA World Cup site |access-date=13 April 2006 |archive-date=19 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220419160212/https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/mens/worldcup/1950brazil |url-status=live }}</ref> A 10–0 home friendly loss against [[England national football team|England]], two years after the war, still stands as their biggest ever defeat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/mundial-2010/artigos/inglaterra-impos-maior-derrota-de-sempre-a-portugal|title=Inglaterra impôs maior derrota de sempre a Portugal|website=SAPO Desporto|access-date=23 September 2019|archive-date=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923160900/https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/mundial-2010/artigos/inglaterra-impos-maior-derrota-de-sempre-a-portugal|url-status=live}}</ref>

===1950s and early 1960s===
Similar to 1934, Portugal [[1950 FIFA World Cup qualification#Group 6|were to play]] a two-legged round against [[Spain national football team|Spain]]. After a 5–1 defeat in Madrid, they managed to draw the second game 2–2. With a 7–3 aggregate score, they did not qualify on the pitch, however they would later be invited to replace [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]], which had withdrawn from participating. Portugal refused to participate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scoreshelf.com/gjdb/en/Spain/World_Cup/1950fwcESP_v_POR|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427091228/http://scoreshelf.com/gjdb/en/Spain/World_Cup/1950fwcESP_v_POR|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 April 2011|title=Spain v Portugal : World Cup 1950 Qualifying Round One|date=27 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scoreshelf.com/gjdb/en/Portugal/World_Cup/1950fwcPOR_v_ESP|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427090855/http://scoreshelf.com/gjdb/en/Portugal/World_Cup/1950fwcPOR_v_ESP|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 April 2011|title=Portugal v Spain : World Cup 1950 Qualifying Round One|date=27 April 2011}}</ref>

In [[1954 FIFA World Cup qualification]], the team would play [[Austria national football team|Austria]]; the Austrians won the first game with a 9–1 result.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scoreshelf.com/gjdb/en/Austria/World_Cup/1954fwcAUT_v_POR|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110426174617/http://scoreshelf.com/gjdb/en/Austria/World_Cup/1954fwcAUT_v_POR|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 April 2011|title=Austria v Portugal : World Cup 1954 Qualifying Round One|date=26 April 2011}}</ref> The best the Portuguese could do was hold the Austrians to a goalless draw in Lisbon, resulting in a 9–1 aggregate defeat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scoreshelf.com/gjdb/en/Portugal/World_Cup/1954fwcPOR_v_AUT|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110426174353/http://scoreshelf.com/gjdb/en/Portugal/World_Cup/1954fwcPOR_v_AUT|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 April 2011|title=Portugal v Austria : World Cup 1954 Qualifying Round One|date=26 April 2011}}</ref> [[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group 8|Four years later]], Portugal won a qualifying match for the first time, a 3–0 home victory over [[Italy national football team|Italy]]. Nevertheless, they finished last in a group that also featured [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]]; only the first-placed team, Northern Ireland, would qualify.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/58qual.html|title=World Cup 1958 qualifications|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|access-date=2 February 2023|archive-date=16 January 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230116104448/https://www.rsssf.org/tables/58qual.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

1960 was the year that UEFA created the [[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]]. The [[1960 European Nations' Cup|first edition]] was a knock-out tournament with the last four teams participating in the finals stage that only featured one leg while the earlier stages had two legs. In the first round, the ''Seleção das Quinas'' won 2–0 at [[East Germany national football team|East Germany]] and then 3–2 in [[Porto]], advancing with a 5–2 two-legged win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/history/seasons/2020/?referrer=%2fuefaeuro%2fseason%3d1960%2fmatches%2fround%3d160%2fmatch%3d4006%2findex|title=German Dem. Rep.-Portugal|website=UEFA.com|publisher=Union of European Football Associations|access-date=19 June 2020|archive-date=23 June 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200623002709/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/match/4006--german-dem-rep-vs-portugal/?referrer=/uefaeuro/season%3D1960/matches/round%3D160/match%3D4006/index|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/history/seasons/2020/?referrer=%2fuefaeuro%2fseason%3d1960%2fmatches%2fround%3d160%2fmatch%3d4007%2findex|title=Portugal-German Dem. Rep.|website=UEFA.com|publisher=Union of European Football Associations|access-date=19 June 2020|archive-date=22 June 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200622050504/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/match/4007--portugal-vs-german-dem-rep/?referrer=/uefaeuro/season%3D1960/matches/round%3D160/match%3D4007/index|url-status=live}}</ref> Portugal faced Yugoslavia in the quarter-finals, losing 6–3 on aggregate.<ref>[http://www1.ionline.pt/conteudo/43822-matateu-ele-e-que-foi-o-d-sebastiao Matateu. Ele é que foi o D. Sebastião (Matateu. The real D. Sebastião)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525210019/http://www1.ionline.pt/conteudo/43822-matateu-ele-e-que-foi-o-d-sebastiao|date=25 May 2012}}; [[i (British newspaper)|''i'']], 27 January 2010 (in Portuguese)</ref>

Portugal faced England and [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] in [[1962 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group 6|1962 FIFA World Cup qualification]] and ended up second in the group, behind England, who would be the only team in Group 6 to qualify.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Cup 1962 qualifications |website=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/62qual.html |access-date=19 June 2020 |archive-date=22 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220922024332/https://www.rsssf.org/tables/62qual.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[1964 European Nations' Cup|1964 European Championship]], Portugal played against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] in the [[1964 European Nations' Cup qualifying|qualifying rounds]]. The Portuguese lost in [[Sofia]] and won in Lisbon. With the round tied 4–4, a replay was needed in a neutral country.<ref name="auto1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/history/seasons/1964/matches/|title=History|website=UEFA.com|publisher=Union of European Football Associations|access-date=19 June 2020|archive-date=22 June 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200622021343/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/history/seasons/1964/matches/|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[Stadio Olimpico]] in Rome, Portugal lost 1–0 thanks to a late strike from [[Georgi Asparuhov]].<ref name="auto1"/>

===Third place at the 1966 World Cup===
Portugal were drawn with [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]], [[Romania national football team|Romania]] and Turkey for [[1966 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group 4|1966 World Cup qualification]].<ref name="1966WC">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/66qual.html|title=World Cup 1966 qualifications|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|access-date=2 February 2023|archive-date=21 February 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230221204752/https://www.rsssf.org/tables/66qual.html|url-status=live}}</ref> They topped the group with only one draw and one defeat in six games and finally qualified for a FIFA World Cup, with a 1–0 away win against Czechoslovakia and Turkey and a 5–1 home win against the Turks being notable results.<ref name="1966WC"/>

At the World Cup, the team started out with three wins in the group stage after they beat [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] 3–1,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/errors/_404?404;https://prd-ne-fe-en__4529:80/worldcup/matches/round=238/match=1675/index|title=FIFA |website=www.fifa.com}}{{dead link|date=October 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Bulgaria 3–0, and two-time defending champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] 3–1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/errors/_404?404;https://prd-ne-fe-en__4529:80/worldcup/matches/round=238/match=1598/index|title=FIFA |website=www.fifa.com}}{{dead link|date=October 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Secondly, they beat quarter-finalists [[North Korea national football team|North Korea]] 5–3, with [[Eusébio]] getting four markers to overturn a 3–0 deficit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsoccer.com/columnists/keir-radnedge/eusebio-344295|title=Portugal legend Eusebio remembered|last=Rainbow|first=Jamie|date=6 January 2014|website=[[World Soccer (magazine)|World Soccer]]|access-date=12 June 2016|archive-date=12 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612220425/http://www.worldsoccer.com/columnists/keir-radnedge/eusebio-344295|url-status=live}}</ref> Later, they reached the semi-finals where they were beaten by hosts England 2–1; in this game, Portugal would have played in [[Liverpool]], but as England were the hosts, FIFA decided that the game would be played in London.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.todoslosmundiales.com.ar/mundiales/1966inglaterra/historias/0036porsitodo.htm |title=Mundial de Inglaterra 1966 – Y POR SI TODO ESTO FUERA POCO |publisher=Todoslosmundiales.com.ar |access-date=3 June 2010 |language=es |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704100453/http://www.todoslosmundiales.com.ar/mundiales/1966inglaterra/historias/0036porsitodo.htm |archive-date=4 July 2010}}</ref> Portugal then defeated the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]] 2–1 in the third place match for their best World Cup finish to date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/errors/_404?404;https://prd-ne-fe-en__4529:80/worldcup/matches/round=3479/match=1709/index|title=FIFA |website=www.fifa.com}}{{dead link|date=October 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Eusébio was the top scorer of the World Cup with nine goals. Portugal would not qualify for another World Cup for 20 years.

===1980s===
Portugal won their [[UEFA Euro 1984 qualifying#Group 2|Euro 1984 qualifying group]] that contained [[Finland national football team|Finland]], Poland and the Soviet Union with a win over the latter,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1984/standings/round=205/group=55/index.html|title=UEFA EURO 1984 - History - Standings – UEFA.com|date=28 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428151017/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1984/standings/round=205/group=55/index.html|archive-date=28 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/84e-qual.html|title=European Championship 1984 - Qualifying - Full Details|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|access-date=2 February 2023|archive-date=30 December 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221230200303/https://www.rsssf.org/tables/84e-qual.html|url-status=live}}</ref> allowing them to qualify and be placed in Group B alongside Spain, [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] and Romania in the finals.<ref name="1984EC">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/news/0253-0d81fe97c09e-c32cda296fe3-1000--euro-on-this-day-19-june/|title=History|date=20 June 2019|website=UEFA.com|publisher=Union of European Football Associations|access-date=19 June 2020|archive-date=7 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200807060332/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/news/0253-0d81fe97c09e-c32cda296fe3-1000--euro-on-this-day-19-june/|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the first two matches, they drew 0–0 and 1–1 against West Germany and Spain, respectively.<ref name="1984EC"/> A 1–0 win over Romania resulted in a second-place finish in group play. Portugal were paired against hosts [[France national football team|France]] in the semi-finals.<ref name="1984EC"/> After a draw in regular time, Portugal initially led 2–1 in extra time, but the hosts scored in the 114th and 119th minutes to eliminate the Portuguese 3–2 and go through to the final.<ref name="1984EC"/>

[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)#Group 2|For 1986 World Cup qualification]], the ''Seleção'' played against Czechoslovakia, [[Malta national football team|Malta]], Sweden and West Germany for the two spots that would guarantee them a ticket to Mexico.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://observador.pt/2014/06/05/o-saltillo-que-se-deu-para-tantos-problemas/ |first=Diogo |last=Pombo |title=O Saltillo que se deu para tantos problemas |date=5 June 2014 |publisher=Observador |access-date=12 October 2017 |archive-date=13 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013070330/http://observador.pt/2014/06/05/o-saltillo-que-se-deu-para-tantos-problemas/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Needing a win in the last game against West Germany in [[Stuttgart]], Portugal won the game to become the first team to beat West Germany at their home ground in an official match. The team exited early in the group stages after a win and two losses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/86full.html|title=World Cup 1986 finals|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|access-date=2 February 2023|archive-date=1 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301052859/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/86full.html|url-status=live}}</ref> They started with a 1–0 win against England,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/errors/_404?404;https://prd-ne-fe-en__4529:80/worldcup/matches/round=308/match=538/index|title=FIFA |website=www.fifa.com}}{{dead link|date=October 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> but later were beaten by Poland and [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] 1–0 and 3–1 respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/errors/_404?404;https://prd-ne-fe-en__4529:80/matches/round=308/match=701/index|title=FIFA |website=www.fifa.com}}{{dead link|date=October 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/errors/_404?404;https://prd-ne-fe-en__4529:80/worldcup/matches/round=308/match=675/index|title=FIFA |website=www.fifa.com}}{{dead link|date=October 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Their staying in Mexico was marked by the [[Saltillo Affair]], where players refused to train in order to win more prizes from the [[Portuguese Football Federation]]. Mexico marked their last World Cup appearance until 2002.

===1995–2006: The golden generation===
At [[UEFA Euro 1996]], Portugal finished first in Group D, and in the [[UEFA Euro 1996 knockout stage#Quarter-finals|quarter-finals]], they lost 1–0 to the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]].

[[File:Charisteas' Siegtreffer im Finale der Euro 2004.jpg|thumb|left|Portugal lost the [[UEFA Euro 2004 final|Euro 2004 final]] 0–1 to Greece with a header from [[Angelos Charisteas]] (pictured).]]

Portugal failed to [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)#Group 9|qualify]] for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. In [[UEFA Euro 2000 qualifying#Group 7|Euro 2000 qualifying]], Portugal finished second in their group, one point short of first-placed Romania. However, after finishing as the top runner-up nation in qualifying, Portugal nonetheless secured a spot in the finals. They then defeated England 3–2, Romania 1–0 and Germany 3–0 to finish first in [[UEFA Euro 2000 Group A|Group A]], then defeated Turkey in the quarter-finals. In the semi-finals against France, Portugal were eliminated in extra time when [[Zinedine Zidane]] converted a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]]. Referee [[Günter Benkö]] awarded the spot kick for a handball after [[Abel Xavier]] blocked a shot. Xavier, [[Nuno Gomes]] and [[Paulo Bento]] were all given lengthy suspensions for subsequently shoving the referee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/euro2000/teams/portugal/815848.stm|title=Uefa suspends Portuguese trio|date=2 July 2000|publisher=BBC|access-date=20 June 2014|archive-date=18 June 2003|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030618220324/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/euro2000/teams/portugal/815848.stm|url-status=live}}</ref> The final eventually finished 2–1.

During [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group 2|2002 FIFA World Cup qualifying]], Portugal won the group.<ref name="FIFA2WC">{{Cite web|url=https://24.sapo.pt/desporto/artigos/mundial-2002-ou-a-historia-de-um-plano-que-afinal-nao-era-perfeito|title=Mundial 2002 ou a história de um plano que afinal não era perfeito|website=SAPO 24|access-date=23 September 2019|archive-date=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923220703/https://24.sapo.pt/desporto/artigos/mundial-2002-ou-a-historia-de-um-plano-que-afinal-nao-era-perfeito|url-status=live}}</ref> Several problems and poor judgement decisions occurred during the preparation and tournament itself and were widely reported in the Portuguese press,<ref name="FIFA2WC"/> including questionable managing choices and some amateurism, as well as lack of agreement on prizes.<ref name="FIFA2WC"/> Portugal entered the tournament as favourites to win Group D.<ref name="FIFA2WC"/> However, they were upset 3–2 by the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]].<ref name="FIFA2WC"/> They then rebounded with a 4–0 victory over Poland.<ref name="FIFA2WC"/> Needing a draw to advance, they lost the last group game to hosts [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/team_pages/portugal/newsid_2047000/2047782.stm|title=Fifa suspends Pinto|date=19 June 2002|publisher=BBC|access-date=1 November 2006|archive-date=18 November 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061118134529/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/team_pages/portugal/newsid_2047000/2047782.stm|url-status=live}}</ref> Portugal underachieved and ended third in its group stage, subsequently eliminated. Manager [[António Oliveira (footballer, born 1952)|António Oliveira]] was fired after the World Cup.

[[File:Cristiano Ronaldo 20120609.jpg|thumb|upright|Ronaldo, pictured playing against [[Germany national football team|Germany]] at [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]], assumed the captaincy in the wake of Euro 2008.]]

The next major competition, the [[UEFA Euro 2004]], was held in Portugal. For preparation, the Football Federation made a contract with [[Luiz Felipe Scolari]] to manage the team until the tournament ended.<ref>{{Cite news |date=28 November 2002 |title=Portugal appoint Big Phil |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/nov/28/newsstory.sport14 |access-date=5 June 2022 |archive-date=5 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220605110146/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/nov/28/newsstory.sport14 |url-status=live }}</ref> The host nation lost the first game against Greece 1–2.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/matches/round=1581/match=1059164/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Greece spoil party for hosts Portugal |work=UEFA |date=13 June 2004 |access-date=7 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709192218/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/matches/round=1581/match=1059164/postmatch/report/index.html |archive-date=9 July 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> They achieved their first win against [[Russia national football team|Russia]] 2–0 and also beat Spain 1–0.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/matches/round=1581/match=1059173/index.html|title=UEFA EURO 2004 - History - Russia-Portugal|date=20 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120021814/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/matches/round=1581/match=1059173/index.html|archive-date=20 January 2012|work=UEFA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/matches/round=1581/match=1059180/index.html|title=UEFA EURO 2004 - History - Spain-Portugal |date=20 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120021824/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/matches/round=1581/match=1059180/index.html|archive-date=20 January 2012|work=UEFA}}</ref> They went on to play against England, in a 2–2 draw that went into penalties, with Portugal winning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/matches/round=1582/match=1059188/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Portugal hold their nerve against England |work=UEFA |date=25 June 2004 |first=Adrian |last=Harte |access-date=23 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419154828/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/matches/round=1582/match=1059188/postmatch/report/index.html |archive-date=19 April 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Portugal beat the Netherlands 2–1 in the semi-finals,<ref>{{cite news |last=McCarra |first=Kevin |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/jul/01/euro2004.sport2 |title=Portugal have the final word |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=1 July 2004 |access-date=25 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204101609/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/jul/01/euro2004.sport2 |archive-date=4 December 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> and suffered a second defeat from Greece, 1–0, in the final.<ref name="Szreter">{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/matches/round=1623/match=1059194/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Greece are crowned kings of Europe |work=UEFA |date=5 July 2004 |first=Adam |last=Szreter |access-date=23 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506130634/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/matches/round=1623/match=1059194/postmatch/report/index.html |archive-date=6 May 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

After the tournament ended, many players belonging to the ''Geração de Ouro'' (Golden Generation), abandoned their international footballing careers, with only [[Luís Figo]] remaining in the team, despite a temporary retirement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/football/news/item/23709-luis-figo-announces-international-retirement|title=Luis Figo announces international retirement|date=19 August 2004|access-date=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928035117/http://sports.ndtv.com/football/news/item/23709-luis-figo-announces-international-retirement|archive-date=28 September 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wldcup.com/news/2005May/20050519_30297_world_soccer.html|title=Figo makes international return|date=19 May 2005}}</ref> The silver lining for Portugal was the emergence of Cristiano Ronaldo, who was selected in the UEFA Euro All-Star team.<ref>{{cite web |title=UEFA EURO 2004 Statistics: Assists |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/statistics/round=1581/players/type=assists/index.html |access-date=9 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202232904/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/statistics/round=1581/players/type=assists/index.html |archive-date=2 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> While Portugal were playing in the competition, Scolari agreed in a new two-year deal with the Federation.

Portugal finished first in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group 3|qualifying round for the 2006 World Cup]],<ref name="Ronaldo profile">{{cite news |title=Cristiano Ronaldo |url=http://www.paktribune.com/sports/fifa2006/playerprofile.php?id=226 |publisher=Paktribune |access-date=14 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209155608/http://www.paktribune.com/sports/fifa2006/playerprofile.php?id=226 |archive-date=9 February 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> and topped Group D in the World Cup, with victories over [[Angola national football team|Angola]] (1–0), [[Iran national football team|Iran]] (2–0) and [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] (2–1).<ref name="Por. Vs Iran">{{cite news |title=Portugal Vs Iran match |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/results/matches/match=97410024/report.html |publisher=FIFA |date=17 June 2006 |access-date=3 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120626140403/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/results/matches/match%3D97410024/report.html |archive-date=26 June 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/worldcup/fixturesresults/round=2259/match=82381/report=rp.html|title=Portugal progress as pool winners|website=UEFA.com|publisher=Union of European Football Associations|date=21 June 2006|access-date=1 April 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070515134812/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/worldcup/fixturesresults/round%3D2259/match%3D82381/report%3Drp.html|archive-date=15 May 2007}}</ref>
Portugal defeated the Netherlands 1–0 in the Round of 16 in an infamous matched that has come to be known as the [[Battle of Nuremberg (2006 FIFA World Cup)|Battle of Nuremberg]], marked by violent fouls and many players [[Penalty card|cautioned]] or [[Ejection (sports)|sent off]] by referee [[Valentin Ivanov (footballer, born 1961)|Valentin Ivanov]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/worldcup/fixturesresults/round=2260/match=84197/report=rp.html|title=''Oranje'' see red as Portugal prevail|website=UEFA.com|publisher=Union of European Football Associations|date=25 June 2006|access-date=1 April 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513183537/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/worldcup/fixturesresults/round%3D2260/match%3D84197/report%3Drp.html|archive-date=13 May 2008}}</ref> Portugal drew 0–0 after extra time with England in the quarter-final, but won 3–1 on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]] to reach their first World Cup semi-final since 1966.<ref>{{cite news |date=4 July 2006 |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=373212 |title=Ronaldo cleared over Rooney red card |work=[[Soccernet]] |access-date=17 November 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110161806/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=373212 |archive-date=10 November 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=97410300/match=97410059/index.html|title=Matches – England-Portugal|work=UEFA|access-date=6 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704153052/https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=97410300/match=97410059/index.html|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Portugal lost the semi-final 1–0 against France,<ref>{{cite web |first=Alex |last=Chick |title=Scolari's fortunes take a dive |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story?id=373430 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140828034241/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story?id=373430 |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 August 2014 |work=ESPNsoccernet |publisher=ESPN |date=6 July 2006 |access-date=25 August 2010 }}</ref> and were then defeated 3–1 by the tournament hosts, Germany, in the third-place play-off match.<ref>[https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991644.stm "Germany 3-1 Portugal"]  . BBC. Retrieved 28 May 2014</ref>

===2006–2014: Post-golden generation and mixed results===
For [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]] Portugal finished second in [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying Group A|qualification]] behind Poland,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2008/standings/round=2241/group=2630/index.html |title=UEFA EURO 2008 - History - Standings – UEFA.com |access-date=23 September 2019 |archive-date=20 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220190735/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2008/standings/round=2241/group=2630/index.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> and won their first two group games against Turkey and the Czech Republic, although a loss to co-hosts Switzerland set up a quarter-final matchup with Germany which the team lost 3–2.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2008/7363493.stm|title=Portugal 2–3 Germany|publisher=BBC Sport|last=McKenzie|first=Andrew|date=19 June 2008|access-date=10 May 2015|archive-date=4 May 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220504124616/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2008/7363493.stm|url-status=live}}</ref> After the tournament, Scolari left to take over at [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/england/2336044/Tough-guy-Scolari-could-also-be-a-loose-cannon.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/england/2336044/Tough-guy-Scolari-could-also-be-a-loose-cannon.html |archive-date=11 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Tough guy Scolari could also be a loose cannon – Telegraph|publisher=telegraph.co.uk|access-date=16 May 2014|last=Winter|first= Henry| location=London | date=28 April 2006}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Afterwards, [[Carlos Queiroz]] was appointed as the head coach of the Portugal national team.<ref name="CQ_Guardian">{{cite news |last=Adamson |first=Mike |title=Queiroz confirmed as Portugal manager |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News and Media |date=11 July 2008 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/jul/11/portugal.manchesterunited |access-date=11 July 2008 |location=London |archive-date=16 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916162409/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/jul/11/portugal.manchesterunited |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="CQ_Reuters_UK">{{cite news |last=Pontes |first=Carlos |title=Queiroz leaves Man United to become Portugal coach |work=uk.reuters.com |publisher=Thomson Reuters |date=12 July 2008 |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idUKL1115675320080711 |access-date=12 July 2008 |archive-date=7 December 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207003103/http://uk.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idUKL1115675320080711 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name="CQ_BBC_Sport">{{cite news |title=Queiroz takes Portugal coach post |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 July 2008 |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/7488580.stm |access-date=11 July 2008 |archive-date=6 September 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906212031/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/7488580.stm |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="CQ_AP">{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |title=Ferguson bids farewell to Queiroz, thanking him for rebuilding the team |series=Sports |work=International Herald Tribune |date=11 July 2008 |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/07/11/sports/EU-SOC-Man-United-Queiroz.php |access-date=11 July 2008}}</ref>

Portugal [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group 1|came second in the qualifying stages]] for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] under Queiroz, then beat [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]] in a [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA second round|play-off]], thereby reaching every tournament in the decade.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/portugal/6607365/Cristiano-Ronaldo-Portugal-star-player-at-World-Cup-2010.html |title=Cristiano Ronaldo: Portugal star player at World Cup 2010 |first=Jonathan |last=Liew |date=20 November 2009 |access-date=23 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509095901/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/portugal/6607365/Cristiano-Ronaldo-Portugal-star-player-at-World-Cup-2010.html |archive-date=9 May 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/errors/_404?404;https://prd-ne-fe-en__4529:80/worldcup/matches/round=253455/match=300110251/report|title=FIFA |website=www.fifa.com}}{{dead link|date=October 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/errors/_404?404;https://prd-ne-fe-en__4529:80/worldcup/matches/round=253455/match=300110247/report|title=FIFA |website=www.fifa.com}}{{dead link|date=October 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> A 19-match undefeated streak, in which the team conceded only three goals, ended with a loss to eventual champions Spain in the round of 16, 1–0.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jun/29/spain-portugal-world-cup-2010-report "World Cup 2010: David Villa raises the roof as Spain push past Portugal"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118105541/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jun/29/spain-portugal-world-cup-2010-report |date=18 November 2018 }}. ''The Guardian'' (London). Retrieved 28 May 2014</ref> Queiroz was later criticised for setting up his team in an overly cautious way.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.record.xl.pt/arquivo/interior.aspx?content_id=446356 |title=.: Deco: "Futebol direto não é o nosso jogo"&nbsp;– Jornal Record :. |publisher=Record.xl.pt |access-date=20 June 2014 |archive-date=6 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406191816/http://www.record.xl.pt/arquivo/interior.aspx?content_id=446356 |url-status=live }}</ref> After the World Cup, squad regulars [[Simão Sabrosa|Simão]], [[Paulo Ferreira]], [[Miguel Monteiro|Miguel]] and [[Tiago Mendes|Tiago]] all retired from international football.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2885/europe/2010/08/27/2090952/portugal-winger-simao-sabrosa-retires-from-international|title=Portugal winger Simao Sabrosa retires from international football|publisher=Goal|date=27 August 2010|access-date=31 August 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100904133337/http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2885/europe/2010/08/27/2090952/portugal-winger-simao-sabrosa-retires-from-international|archive-date=4 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/8957097.stm|title=Chelsea's Paulo Ferreira quits Portuguese national team|publisher=BBC Sport|date=31 August 2010|access-date=22 May 2013|archive-date=27 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227063054/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/8957097.stm|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsf.pt/desporto/interior/tiago-renuncia-a-seleccao-nacional-1759460.html|title=Tiago renuncia à selecção nacional|trans-title=Tiago renounces national team|publisher=[[TSF (radio station)|TSF]]|language=pt|date=17 January 2011|access-date=4 April 2018|archive-date=5 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405152817/https://www.tsf.pt/desporto/interior/tiago-renuncia-a-seleccao-nacional-1759460.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Queiroz was banned from coaching the national team for one month after he tried to block a doping test to the team while preparing for the World Cup, as well as directing insulting words to the testers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.record.xl.pt/Futebol/selecoes//interior.aspx?content_id=457989 |title=.: Carlos Queiroz suspenso por um mês&nbsp;– Jornal Record :. |publisher=Record.xl.pt |date=18 August 2010 |access-date=20 June 2014 |archive-date=7 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407085222/http://www.record.xl.pt/Futebol/selecoes//interior.aspx?content_id=457989 |url-status=live }}</ref> In consequence, he received a further six-month suspension. Several media outbursts from Queiroz<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.record.xl.pt/Futebol/selecoes//interior.aspx?content_id=458171 |title=.: Processo disciplinar a Carlos Queiroz&nbsp;– Jornal Record :. |publisher=Record.xl.pt |access-date=20 June 2014 |archive-date=7 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407084952/http://www.record.xl.pt/Futebol/selecoes//interior.aspx?content_id=458171 |url-status=live }}</ref> against the heads of the Portuguese Football Federation followed, which partly prompted his dismissal. Paulo Bento was appointed as his replacement at head coach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abola.pt/nnh/ver.aspx?id=223070 |title=abola.pt |publisher=abola.pt |date=6 June 2014 |access-date=20 June 2014 |archive-date=4 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504173602/http://www.abola.pt/nnh/ver.aspx?id=223070 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Bento's team qualified for Euro 2012; they were drawn with Germany, Denmark, and the Netherlands in a widely speculated "[[group of death]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/sports/soccer/news/_/id/7306118/euro-2012-group-group-breakdown-predictions-which-teams-go-ravi-ubha|title=Euro 2012 group-by-group breakdown|last=Ubha|first=Ravi|date=2 December 2011|publisher=ESPN|access-date=3 December 2011|archive-date=22 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422163905/http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/news/_/id/7306118/euro-2012-group-group-breakdown-predictions-which-teams-go-ravi-ubha|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/sports/soccer/news/_/id/7303709/euro-2012-storylines-follow-poland-ukraine-james-tyler|title=The real attractions of Euro 2012|last=James|first=Tyler|date=2 December 2011|publisher=ESPN|access-date=3 December 2011|archive-date=4 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111204235527/http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/news/_/id/7303709/euro-2012-storylines-follow-poland-ukraine-james-tyler|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/united/euro-2012-draw-germany-netherlands-portugal-denmark-land-in-group-of-death/2011/12/02/gIQARWLrLO_gallery.html#photo=1|title=Euro 2012 Draw: Germany, the Netherlands, Portugal, Denmark land in "Group of Death"|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=3 December 2011|archive-date=4 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150504225221/http://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/united/euro-2012-draw-germany-netherlands-portugal-denmark-land-in-group-of-death/2011/12/02/gIQARWLrLO_gallery.html#photo=1|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livesoccertv.com/news/4747/uefa-euro-2012-group-of-death-germany-with-portugal-holland-who-ll-be-doomed/|title=UEFA Euro 2012 Group of Death: Germany with Portugal & Holland. Who'll be doomed?|last=Asante|first=Angela|date=2 December 2011|publisher=Livesoccertv|access-date=3 December 2011|archive-date=30 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120430200211/http://www.livesoccertv.com/news/4747/uefa-euro-2012-group-of-death-germany-with-portugal-holland-who-ll-be-doomed/|url-status=live}}</ref> They lost their first game 0–1 to Germany, then beat Denmark 3–2.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2012/6/9/3075276/germany-vs-portugal-final-score-match-report-live-streaming-updates-euro-2012|title=Germany vs Portugal, Euro 2012: final score|last=McCauley|first=Kevin|date=9 June 2012|publisher=SB Nation|access-date=18 June 2012|archive-date=13 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120613171119/http://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2012/6/9/3075276/germany-vs-portugal-final-score-match-report-live-streaming-updates-euro-2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2012/6/13/3083248/denmark-vs-portugal-final-score-match-report-recap-euro-2012|title=Denmark vs Portugal, Euro 2012: final score|last=McCauley|first=Kevin|date=13 June 2012|publisher=SB Nation|access-date=18 June 2012|archive-date=15 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615223346/http://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2012/6/13/3083248/denmark-vs-portugal-final-score-match-report-recap-euro-2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The final group stage match was against the Netherlands. After [[Rafael van der Vaart|Van der Vaart]] had given the Dutch a 1–0 lead, Ronaldo netted twice to ensure a 2–1 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Euro 2012: Nani springs to Cristiano Ronaldo's defence after criticism |first=Stuart |last=James |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/jun/15/euro-2012-nani-cristiano-ronaldo?newsfeed=true |newspaper=The Guardian |date=15 June 2012 |access-date=21 June 2012 |archive-date=10 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310020959/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/jun/15/euro-2012-nani-cristiano-ronaldo?newsfeed=true |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cristiano Ronaldo under mounting pressure to perform for Portugal at Euro 2012 |first=Martin |last=Rogers |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/cristiano-ronaldo-under-mounting-pressure-to-perform-for-portugal-at-euro-2012.html |publisher=Yahoo Sports |date=12 June 2012 |access-date=21 June 2012 |archive-date=15 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615194608/http://sports.yahoo.com/news/cristiano-ronaldo-under-mounting-pressure-to-perform-for-portugal-at-euro-2012.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/17/portugal-netherlands-euro-2012-cristiano-ronaldo_n_1604271.html|title=Portugal beats Netherlands 2–1 at Euro 2012|last=Hatton|first=Barry|date=17 June 2012|work=Huffington Post|access-date=18 June 2012|archive-date=19 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619201825/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/17/portugal-netherlands-euro-2012-cristiano-ronaldo_n_1604271.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Portugal finished second in the group and qualified for the knockout phase. Portugal defeated the Czech Republic 1–0 in the quarter-finals with a header from Ronaldo.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/euro-2012/euro-2012-cristiano-ronaldo-header-sends-portugal-semifinals-1-0-win-czech-republic-article-1.1100074 |title=Euro 2012: Cristiano Ronaldo's header sends Portugal into semi-finals with 1–0 win over Czech Republic |work=Daily News |location=New York |date=21 June 2012 |access-date=26 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120624235350/http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/euro-2012/euro-2012-cristiano-ronaldo-header-sends-portugal-semifinals-1-0-win-czech-republic-article-1.1100074 |archive-date=24 June 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The semi-final match was against Spain, who defeated Portugal 4–2 on penalties after a goalless draw.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/euro-2012/euro-2012-defending-champion-spain-advances-final-beating-portugal-4-2-penalties-article-1.1103477 |title=Euro 2012: Defending champion Spain advances to another final after beating Portugal 4–2 on penalties |work=Daily News |location=New York |date=27 June 2012 |access-date=28 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120629092504/http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/euro-2012/euro-2012-defending-champion-spain-advances-final-beating-portugal-4-2-penalties-article-1.1103477 |archive-date=29 June 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2014 FIFA World Cup qualifying]], Portugal won 4–2 on aggregate in a play-off against Sweden with all four goals being scored by Ronaldo, and were drawn into [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group G|Group G]] with the United States, Germany and [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]. Their first match against the Germans was their worst-ever defeat in a World Cup, a 4–0 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/world-cup/eye-on-world-cup/24585479/fifa-world-cup-portugal-vs-germany-preview|title=2014 FIFA World Cup: Germany dominates Portugal, 4–0|last=Borzello|first=Joe|date=16 June 2014|work=CBS Sports|access-date=16 June 2014|archive-date=4 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304110421/http://www.cbssports.com/world-cup/eye-on-world-cup/24585479/fifa-world-cup-portugal-vs-germany-preview|url-status=dead}}</ref> They went on to draw 2–2 against the United States and won 2–1 against Ghana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/errors/_404?404;https://prd-ne-fe-en__4529:80/worldcup/matches/round=255931/match=300186483/index|title=FIFA |website=www.fifa.com}}{{dead link|date=October 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name="BBC14">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25285312 "Portugal 2–1 Ghana"] . BBC Sport. Retrieved 26 June 2014</ref> However, the team were eliminated due to inferior goal difference to the Americans.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/25285312|title=Portugal 2 Ghana 1|work=BBC Sport|date=26 June 2014|access-date=23 September 2019|archive-date=27 February 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230227153809/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/25285312|url-status=live}}</ref>
