In [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]], Bento was dismissed following a defeat to Albania and was replaced by [[Fernando Santos (footballer, born 1954)|Fernando Santos]] in September 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Portugal coach Paulo Bento leaves role after shock Albania defeat|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29167243|access-date=11 September 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 September 2014|archive-date=11 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911194104/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29167243|url-status=live}}</ref> After qualifying for the finals, Portugal finished third in Group F but advanced to the knockout stages as the third-best third place team following three straight draws. Portugal beat Croatia 1–0 after extra time in the round of 16<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/croatia-vs-portugal-euro-2016-match-report-ricardo-quaresmas-late-strike-settles-dreadful-encounter-a7103531.html|title=Croatia vs Portugal Euro 2016 match report: Ricardo Quaresma's late strike settles dreadful encounter after a Cristiano Ronaldo rebound|date=25 June 2016|work=The Independent|first=Jack|last=Pitt-Brooke|publisher=ESI Media|access-date=5 December 2017|archive-date=21 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180221103138/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/croatia-vs-portugal-euro-2016-match-report-ricardo-quaresmas-late-strike-settles-dreadful-encounter-a7103531.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and then defeated Poland 5–3 on penalties to reach the semi-finals,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/poland-portugal-euro-2016-robert-lewandowski-cristiano-ronaldo-a7112346.html|title=Lewandowski finally gets off the mark, but Portugal beat Poland on penalties|date=30 June 2016|work=The Independent|first=Tim|last=Rich|access-date=5 December 2017|archive-date=20 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220212517/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/poland-portugal-euro-2016-robert-lewandowski-cristiano-ronaldo-a7112346.html|url-status=live}}</ref> where they defeated [[Wales national football team|Wales]] 2–0.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/portugal-wales-match-report-cristiano-ronaldo-a7123796.html|title=Ronaldo breaks Welsh hearts and sends Portugal to Paris|date=6 July 2016|first=Mark|last=Ogden|work=The Independent|access-date=5 December 2017|archive-date=21 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180221101611/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/portugal-wales-match-report-cristiano-ronaldo-a7123796.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[UEFA Euro 2016 final|final]] against the hosts, France, Ronaldo went off injured. In extra time, substitute [[Eder (footballer, born 1987)|Eder]] scored the winning goal for Portugal in the 109th minute with a strike from 25 yards past [[Hugo Lloris]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36696772|title=Portugal 1 France 0|date=10 July 2016|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=11 July 2016|archive-date=10 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710233341/http://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36696772|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2016/jul/10/cristiano-ronaldo-tears-portugal-greatest-night|title=Cristiano Ronaldo's tears of sadness turn to joy on Portugal's greatest night|date=10 July 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=11 July 2016|first=David|last=Hytner|archive-date=22 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210122075715/https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2016/jul/10/cristiano-ronaldo-tears-portugal-greatest-night|url-status=live}}</ref>

Following their [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]] victory, Portugal participated in the [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup]]. They finished top of their group,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40393539 |title=Confederations Cup: Ronaldo helps Portugal into semi-final as hosts Russia out |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 June 2017 |access-date=24 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628001450/http://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40393539 |archive-date=28 June 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/news/0253-0d81f47dfe05-e92503acfb7d-1000--europe-s-top-international-scorers-cristiano-ronaldo-out-in-/ |title=Ronaldo second on all-time list of international scorers |website=UEFA.com|publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=24 June 2017 |access-date=24 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623154956/http://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/news/newsid=2412422.html |archive-date=23 June 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> but lost to [[Chile national football team|Chile]] on penalties after a goalless draw in the [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup#Semi-finals|semi-finals]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/portugal/story/3150221/cristiano-ronaldo-leaves-confederations-cup-to-meet-his-new-twins |title=Cristiano Ronaldo confirms birth of twins, leaves Portugal at Confed Cup |work=ESPN FC |date=29 June 2017 |access-date=30 June 2017 |last=Corrigan |first=Dermot |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702045441/http://www.espnfc.com/portugal/story/3150221/cristiano-ronaldo-leaves-confederations-cup-to-meet-his-new-twins |archive-date=2 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> but rebounded in the [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup#Third place play-off|third place game]], defeating Mexico 2–1 after extra time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/matches/round=274643/match=300334886/match-report.html |title=Portugal come from behind to finish third |publisher=FIFA |date=2 July 2017 |access-date=2 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702174315/http://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/matches/round=274643/match=300334886/match-report.html |archive-date=2 July 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

[[File:Portugal national football team World Cup 2018.jpg|thumb|Portugal lining up before a match at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]]]]

At the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], Portugal opened their campaign with a 3–3 draw with Spain, with Cristiano Ronaldo scoring a [[List of FIFA World Cup hat-tricks|hat-trick]].<ref name="cbssports.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/world-cup/news/spain-vs-portugal-final-score-crazy-draw-as-ronaldo-becomes-oldest-to-score-world-cup-hat-trick/amp/|title=Spain vs. Portugal final score: Crazy draw as Cristiano Ronaldo becomes oldest to score World Cup hat trick|work=CBS Sports|date=16 June 2018 |access-date=16 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616031345/https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/world-cup/news/spain-vs-portugal-final-score-crazy-draw-as-ronaldo-becomes-oldest-to-score-world-cup-hat-trick/amp/|archive-date=16 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> After a 1–0 victory against Morocco,<ref>{{cite web |title=Ronaldo grabs winner, Morocco eliminated |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/match/300331511/#match-summary |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612214454/https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/match/300331511/#match-summary |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 June 2018 |publisher=FIFA.com |date=20 June 2018}}</ref> Portugal drew 1–1 with Iran to progress to the knockout round as group runners-up.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44439228 |title=Iran 1 – 1 Portugal |publisher=BBC Sport|last=Henry |first=Matthew |date=25 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712111916/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44439228 |archive-date=12 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Portugal were eliminated following a 2–1 defeat to [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup knockout stage|round of 16]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jun/30/uruguay-portugal-world-cup-last-16-match-report|title=Edinson Cavani sends Uruguay to World Cup last eight as Portugal bow out|last=Lowe|first=Sid|date=30 June 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=30 June 2018|archive-date=3 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503072504/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jun/30/uruguay-portugal-world-cup-last-16-match-report|url-status=live}}</ref>

Following the World Cup, Portugal won the inaugural [[2018–19 UEFA Nations League|UEFA Nations League]] beating the Netherlands at the [[Estádio do Dragão]] in Porto, with the only goal scored by [[Gonçalo Guedes]] in the 60th minute.<ref name="Sports Mole">{{cite news |last1=Law |first1=Matt |title=Result: Goncalo Guedes scores winner as Portugal land UEFA Nations League title |url=https://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/portugal/uefa-nations-league/result/result-guedes-scores-winner-as-portugal-land-nations-league-title_361579.html |access-date=9 June 2019 |work=Sports Mole |date=9 June 2019 |archive-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407090720/https://www.sportsmole.co.uk/fb_361579.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48191922|title=Nations League final: Portugal 1-0 Netherlands|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Shamoon|last=Hafez|date=9 June 2019|access-date=10 June 2019|archive-date=1 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210601184142/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48191922|url-status=live}}</ref>

At [[UEFA Euro 2020]], Portugal were drawn into a group containing [[France national football team|France]], [[Germany national football team|Germany]] and [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] which was widely speculated as being the "group of death".{{Citation needed|date=April 2025}} Portugal advanced to the [[UEFA Euro 2020 knockout stage|next round]] by defeating Hungary, drawing with France and losing to Germany. There, they faced [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] but lost 1–0.

For the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group A|2022 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]], Portugal were required to qualify for the finals via the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA second round|play-offs]] after finishing second in their group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59282726|title=Portugal 1 Serbia 2|date=14 November 2021|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 November 2021|archive-date=25 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220325205014/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59282726|url-status=live}}</ref> Nevertheless, Portugal managed to beat [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Diogo Costa e a titularidade frente à Turquia: "Foi muito especial para mim" |trans-title=Diogo Costa and the starting role against Turkey: "It was very special for me" |url=https://www.record.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/mundial/mundial-2022/detalhe/diogo-costa-e-a-titularidade-frente-a-turquia-foi-muito-especial-para-mim |access-date=29 March 2022 |work=Record |date=24 March 2022 |language=Portuguese |archive-date=29 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220329224637/https://www.record.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/mundial/mundial-2022/detalhe/diogo-costa-e-a-titularidade-frente-a-turquia-foi-muito-especial-para-mim |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[North Macedonia national football team|North Macedonia]] to qualify for the final tournament.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernandes |first1=Mariana |last2=Paredes |first2=Diogo |title=Portugal vence Macedónia do Norte com bis de Bruno Fernandes e está no Mundial do Qatar (2-0) - como aconteceu |trans-title=Portugal defeat North Macedonia with a brace from Bruno Fernandes and are in the World Cup in Qatar (2-0) - how it happened |url=https://observador.pt/liveblogs/portugal-macedonia-do-norte-danilo-mantem-se-a-central-ao-lado-de-pepe-diogo-costa-volta-a-ser-titular-na-baliza/ |access-date=29 March 2022 |work=Observador |date=29 March 2022 |language=Portuguese |archive-date=29 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220329175540/https://observador.pt/liveblogs/portugal-macedonia-do-norte-danilo-mantem-se-a-central-ao-lado-de-pepe-diogo-costa-volta-a-ser-titular-na-baliza/ |url-status=live }}</ref> At the 2022 World Cup, Portugal defeated [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] 3–2 in their first group game<ref>{{Cite web |title=Portugal vs. Ghana - Football Match Report - November 24, 2022 - ESPN |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/633800 |access-date=2022-12-29 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |archive-date=29 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221229095919/https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/633800 |url-status=live }}</ref> and then beat Uruguay 2–0.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Portugal vs. Uruguay - Football Match Report - November 28, 2022 - ESPN |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/633817 |access-date=2022-12-15 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |archive-date=15 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221215191844/https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/633817 |url-status=live }}</ref> to qualify for the knockout stages.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Whitehead |first=Jacob |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3946148/2022/11/28/portugal-uruguay-result/ |title=Portugal vs Uruguay result: Fernandes double secures progression for Portuguese |date=28 November 2022 |access-date=28 November 2022 |work=ESPN |archive-date=28 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221128210416/https://theathletic.com/3946148/2022/11/28/portugal-uruguay-result/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The Portuguese would demolish [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] 6–1 in the next round, their highest tally in a World Cup knockout game since the [[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966 World Cup]], with [[Gonçalo Ramos]] scoring a hat-trick.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Jolly |first=Richard |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/cristiano-ronaldo-portugal-b2240179.html |title=Cristiano Ronaldo shocked by seismic shift in Portugal's World Cup pecking order |date=6 December 2022 |access-date=6 December 2022 |work=[[The Independent]] |archive-date=12 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221212104418/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/cristiano-ronaldo-portugal-b2240179.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Photos: Portugal 6, Switzerland 1 – (Ronaldo 0) |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/gallery/2022/12/7/photos-portugal-vs-switzerland |access-date=2022-12-15 |website=www.aljazeera.com |language=en |archive-date=15 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221215191846/https://www.aljazeera.com/gallery/2022/12/7/photos-portugal-vs-switzerland |url-status=live }}</ref> However, they were eliminated by tournament in the quarter-finals by [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]], 1–0.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Morocco beat Portugal to make World Cup history |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63843785 |access-date=2022-12-15 |archive-date=19 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221219015323/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63843785 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following a disappointing World Cup campaign, Fernando Santos was dismissed on 15 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/sports/portugal-coach-fernando-santos-set-leave-job-after-world-cup-defeat-source-2022-12-15/|title=Portugal coach Santos leaves job after World Cup exit|publisher=Reuters|last=Demony|first=Catarina|date=15 December 2022|access-date=15 December 2022|archive-date=15 December 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221215190532/https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/sports/portugal-coach-fernando-santos-set-leave-job-after-world-cup-defeat-source-2022-12-15/|url-status=live}}</ref> 

===2023–present: Martinez era and Second Nations League title===
On 9 January 2023, [[Roberto Martínez|Roberto Martinez]] was announced as the new head coach of Portugal.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4066354/2023/01/07/roberto-martinez-portugal-head-coach/ | title=Martinez reaches verbal agreement to become Portugal head coach | access-date=29 March 2023 | archive-date=24 March 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230324030407/https://theathletic.com/4066354/2023/01/07/roberto-martinez-portugal-head-coach/ | url-status=live | last1=Ornstein | first1=David | work=The New York Times | date=7 January 2023 }}</ref> On 11 September, Martinez led Portugal to their biggest victory in international history by defeating [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] 9–0 at home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/portugal/selecao-nacional/portugal-9-0-luxemburgo-cronica|title=Portugal 9–0 Luxemburgo (crónica)|trans-title=Portugal 9–0 Luxembourg (report)|publisher=Mais Futebol|first=Pedro|last=Lemos|language=pt|date=11 September 2023|access-date=11 September 2023}}</ref> Martinez's Portuguese side were one of the first European sides to advance from qualifying into the [[UEFA Euro 2024]] after their 3–2 win over [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]], making it their quickest qualification to a major tournament in their history.<ref>{{cite news |date=13 October 2023 |title=Portugal carimba qualificação para o Euro 2024 — com muitos recordes à mistura |url=https://zap.aeiou.pt/portugal-qualificacao-euro-2024-recordes-562063 |access-date=14 October 2023 |newspaper=ZAP}}</ref> Following a 2–0 home over Iceland, Martinez led Portugal to a perfect qualification campaign, overtaking the record for most scored and least scored against in a qualifying campaign in the country's history, with a record of 36 goals scored and only two goals conceded, keeping nine clean sheets in the process. Portugal also became one of the few European national teams to win all of their matches for the qualifiers of the [[UEFA European Championship]], with ten wins from ten matches, the first time in Portugal's international history.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=19 November 2023 |title=Roberto Martínez: dez meses e vários recordes batidos na caminhada para o Europeu|trans-title=Roberto Martínez: ten months and several records broken on the way to the European Championship|url=https://www.dn.pt/desporto/roberto-martinez-dez-meses-e-varios-recordes-batidos-na-caminhada-para-o-europeu-17366632.html|access-date=25 November 2023 |website= |publisher=[[Diário de Notícias]] |language=pt-pt}}</ref>

In their European Championship group, Portugal were paired with [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]], [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] and [[Czech Republic national football team|Czechia]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=UEFA.com |title=UEFA EURO 2024 final tournament draw |url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/draws/ |access-date=2024-07-09 |website=[[UEFA]] |language=en}}</ref> With wins against Czechia and Turkey and a loss to Georgia, Portugal qualified for the Round of 16 as group winners, where they played against [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]]. The game finished 0–0 and was decided on penalties, with Portuguese goalkeeper [[Diogo Costa]] saving each of Slovenia's penalties, while Portugal scored all of theirs.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Murray |first=Scott |date=2024-07-01 |title=Portugal 0-0 Slovenia (aet; pens 3-0): Euro 2024, last 16 – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2024/jul/01/portugal-v-slovenia-euro-2024-last-16-live |access-date=2024-07-09 |work=the Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Facing [[France national football team|France]] in the Quarter finals, the game again finished 0–0 and was decided on penalties; a miss by [[João Félix|João Felix]] meant France won 5–3, and Portugal were eliminated.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Portugal vs France LIVE: France reach Euro 2024 semi-finals after penalty shootout win - reaction & stats |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cy79llev4znt |access-date=2024-07-09 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 9 June 2025, Roberto Martinez guided Portugal to their second [[UEFA Nations League]] title after defeating the reigning European champions Spain 5–3 on penalties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/match/2044949--portugal-vs-spain/|title=Portugal-Spain &#124; UEFA Nations League 2025 Final |website=UEFA.com}}</ref>

==Team image==
===Kits===
{{Commons|Portugal national football team kits}}
Portugal's traditional [[kit (association football)|home kit]] is mainly red with a green trim, reflecting the colours of the nation's [[Flag of Portugal|flag]]. Over the years, the particular shade of red has alternated between a darker [[Burgundy (color)|burgundy]] and a lighter [[Scarlet (color)|scarlet]]. Both green and red shorts have been used to complete the strip.

The team's away kits, on the other hand, have varied more considerably. White has typically been preferred as a dominant colour, either with blue shorts, or red and green highlights. In recent times, all-black has been utilised, as has a turquoise-teal colour, the latter of which was prominently featured during the title winning [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]] campaign.

